To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, we can use the `tikz` package to create a grid and then place the chess pieces using the `chessboard` package. Here's an example code that uses the FEN notation to set up the initial position of the pieces:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\useasboundingbox (-3,-3) rectangle (11,11);
\foreach \x in {-2,-1.5,...,11} {
  \foreach \y in {-3,-2.5,...,11} {
    \draw (\x,\y) -- (\x+0.5,\y+0.5) -- (\x+0.5,\y+1) -- (\x,\y+1) -- cycle;
  }
}
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\setchessboard [fen=startfen] [cols=8, rows=8]
\chessboard [showmover=false, setfen=true]
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this code, we first define a `tikzpicture` environment with a bounding box that matches the dimensions of the chessboard. We then create a grid of squares using a nested loop that iterates over all the x and y coordinates. Finally, we use the `setchessboard` command to set up the initial position of the pieces based on the FEN notation.

To use this code, replace `startfen` with the desired FEN notation string. For example, the initial position of the pieces can be represented by the following FEN notation:

```
rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1
```

