In Java, the `==` operator is used for reference comparison, which means it checks whether two variables refer to the same object in memory. When comparing strings, it is generally better to use the `equals()` method instead.

The `equals()` method is defined in the `String` class and compares the contents of two strings, rather than their memory locations. This means that using `equals()` to compare strings is both more efficient and more accurate than using `==`.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```java
String str1 = "hello";
String str2 = "hello";
String str3 = new String("hello");

if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are the same object");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not the same object");
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not equal");
}

if (str1 == str3) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are the same object");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are not the same object");
}

if (str1.equals(str3)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are equal");
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str3 are not equal");
}
```

Output:
```
str1 and str2 are not the same object
str1 and str2 are equal
